data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration is required here.**

Your code uses only `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which are affected by the .NET 6+ breaking change. These APIs work identically on .NET 8. The code will compile and run correctly as-is on your target framework.

---

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort):

If you'd like to simplify the code using modern .NET idioms, you could replace the manual thread management with `Parallel.ForEach`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This is purely optional — it reduces boilerplate and uses the thread pool efficiently, but is not required for the .NET 8 migration to succeed.
